Manux
=====
Manux is a hobby kernel written in Z80 assembly and C. It's designed to be small and simple. It will only support monotasking. The kernel includes `unistd` for cross-platform compatibility. It currently supports very basic IO, but new features will be added in the future.
So don't expect it to be Linux 2.0.

Kernel API
==========
All system calls must be called from user mode. The system call vector is at 0xB000. It's at that address because the kernel is designed to be loaded from BASIC.

POSIX
=====
Manux can run very simple POSIX programs. However, it's not fully POSIX-compliant, so it may not work with some programs. Currently the supported features are input/output, fork, and exec.

Minimum system requirements
====================
- Z80 CPU
- 8K RAM
- 8K ROM (not required if booting from BASIC)
- a serial interface

TODO
====
- Better kernel loader for BASIC
- Heap manager
- Reorganize kernel functions
- Minimal Z80 assembler(supports only the main instructions)

Tips for writing efficient code
===============================
- Use 8-bit and 16-bit variables if possible
- Use preincrement/decrement when possible

Pre-requisites
=============
- z88dk (nightly builds are recommended)
- make
- kconfig-frontends-nox

Building
========

To build Manux, run `make`. The kernel is build with z88dk. You need to have z88dk installed to build the kernel. TODO: configuration script

